## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Core Problem

`Thread.Abort()` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+. They were removed because thread aborts corrupt process state — they can fire mid-`finally`, mid-`catch`, or inside `lock` blocks.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Wait throws OperationCanceledException if the token fires
            // before the task starts, or TimeoutException via our check.
            if (!task.Wait(timeout))
            {
                cts.Cancel();
                throw new TimeoutException(
                    $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
            }
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single exceptions to match original behavior
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }

        return task.Result;
    }

    // Preferred: async version with cooperative cancellation
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Sync (fire-and-forget warning: work may keep running after timeout)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveComputation(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async with cooperative cancellation (preferred — clean shutdown)
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    await foreach (var item in source.WithCancellation(ct))
        Process(item);
    return finalResult;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` ignores the token, it keeps running after timeout. There is no safe replacement for forced abort in .NET 8. |
| **`Task.Run` + `CancellationToken`** | The token only prevents *starting* a queued task. It does **not** interrupt already-running code. You must pass `CancellationToken` into the work itself. |
| **`default(T)` race condition** | The original code had a race: `result` could be read as `default` if the thread was aborted mid-assignment. The `Task`-based version avoids this — `task.Result` is thread-safe. |
| **Thread pool starvation** | The original used a dedicated thread. `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. For long-blocking work, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` gone** | Any `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks are dead code in .NET 8. Replace with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |
| **`ResetAbort()` gone** | Code calling `Thread.ResetAbort()` will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime (not a compile error — it still exists as an API surface). |

### If You Truly Need Forced Termination

The only safe option is **process isolation**:

```csharp
// Run untrusted/uncooperative work in a child process
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("Worker process timed out");
}
```

**Bottom line:** Migrate to the async/cooperative cancellation pattern wherever possible. The sync wrapper works as a drop-in but cannot guarantee the work actually stops on timeout.
